pensing with the notion of shared ‘humanitarian’ ideals, it examines the complex, and sometimes controversial, origins of organised relief, and illuminates the emergence of practices and protocols still recognisable in the delivery of overseas aid. This book is intended for students, academics and relief practitioners interested in the historical concerns of first generation relief agencies such as the British Red Cross Society and the Save the Children Fund, and their legacies today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanitarian assistance, BritishxHistoryy19th century. 0aHumanitarian assistance, BritishxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar reliefzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aWar reliefzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar victimsxServices forxHistoryy19th century. 0aWar victimsxServices forxHistoryy20th century. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aBalkans.  aBoer War.  aBritish colonial wars.  aBritish concentration camps.  aBritish policy.  aBritish soldiers.  aFranco-Prussian War.  aLoyd Lindsay.  aOttoman counter-insurgency.  aRusso-Turkish War.  aSouth Africa.  achild welfare.  ahumanity.  anationalist violence.  anineteenth-century relief workers.  apost-war period.  arelief work.1 aGill, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611065740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526110657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526110657/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles